{"meta":{"updateDate":1755117017717,"pPcc":"SAT#H","questionId":"2869fe95","skill_cd":"H.E.","score_band_range_cd":2,"skill_desc":"Linear inequalities in one or two variables","createDate":1755117017717,"program":"SAT","primary_class_cd_desc":"Algebra","ibn":"","external_id":"3f8fee7b-88df-4e61-b457-3a88934cb9c7","primary_class_cd":"H","uId":"c12bccba-62e0-4c64-b7c0-3e4d03db04e1","difficulty":"E"},"source":"modern","detail":{"type":"mcq","stem":"<p style=\"text-align: left;\">For a <math alttext=\"3\"><mn>3</mn>\n</math>-week period in a town in Illinois, the lowest recorded temperature was <math alttext=\"31\"><mn>31</mn>\n</math> degrees Fahrenheit <math alttext=\"left parenthesis degree upper F right parenthesis\"><mfenced><mrow><mo>&#176;</mo><mtext>F</mtext></mrow></mfenced></math> and the highest recorded temperature was <math alttext=\"67 degree upper F\"><mn>67</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mtext>F</mtext></math>. Which inequality is true for any recorded temperature <math alttext=\"t\"><mi>t</mi>\n</math>, in <math alttext=\"degree upper F\"><mo>&#176;</mo><mtext>F</mtext></math>, in this town for this <math alttext=\"3\"><mn>3</mn>\n</math>-week period?</p>","keys":["89824bd7-8fdc-47cf-a85b-ea565bc07129"],"answerOptions":[{"id":"bb3fc3c7-3a59-4561-81ee-c62438e3adc9","content":"<p><math alttext=\"t greater than or equals 98\"><mi>t</mi><mo>&#8805;</mo><mn>98</mn></math></p>"},{"id":"b6439e52-c2ea-40f1-a25d-8dc31c3eddc8","content":"<p><math alttext=\"t greater than or equals 67\"><mi>t</mi><mo>&#8805;</mo><mn>67</mn></math></p>"},{"id":"89824bd7-8fdc-47cf-a85b-ea565bc07129","content":"<p><math alttext=\"31 less than or equals t less than or equals 67\"><mn>31</mn><mo>&#8804;</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>&#8804;</mo><mn>67</mn></math></p>"},{"id":"1b3e1a03-47ec-4902-8f18-170545520967","content":"<p><math alttext=\"t less than or equals 31\"><mi>t</mi><mo>&#8804;</mo><mn>31</mn></math></p>"}],"rationale":"<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Choice C is correct. It's given that for a <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"3\"><mn>3</mn></math>-week period in a town in Illinois, the lowest recorded temperature was <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"31 degree upper F\"><mn>31</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mtext>F</mtext></math> and the highest recorded temperature was <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"67 degree upper F\"><mn>67</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mtext>F</mtext></math>. It follows that the inequality <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"31 less than or equals t less than or equals 67\"><mn>31</mn><mo>&#8804;</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>&#8804;</mo><mn>67</mn></math> is true for any recorded temperature <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"t\"><mi>t</mi></math>, in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"degree upper F\"><mo>&#176;</mo><mtext>F</mtext></math>, in this town for this <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"3\"><mn>3</mn></math>-week period.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Choice A is incorrect and may result from conceptual errors.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Choice B is incorrect and may result from conceptual errors.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Choice D is incorrect and may result from conceptual errors.</p>","externalid":"3f8fee7b-88df-4e61-b457-3a88934cb9c7","correct_answer":["C"]}}